description.narrative:
Agriculture is the main livelihood activity and source of food for households, especially in the northern part of Tanganyika. Agricultural production is mainly focused on cassava and maize (both for sale and consumption), making smallholder farmers and consumers more vulnerable to sudden shocks (shortages, hazards/weather and other negative factors).
Agriculture (62%) and markets (32%) are the two main sources of household food. The establishment of mining companies in northern Tanganyika provides an opportunity for smallholder farmers to sell surplus production in order to increase income. However, this may also be a demotivating factor, leading to the abandonment of agricultural activities in favour of mining.
The inter-ethnic conflict between the Twa and Bantu ethnic groups has been ongoing for almost a decade and is the primary cause of population displacements. This conflict has led to the loss of livelihoods and widespread impoverishment of households and the deterioration of basic community infrastructure, including the social system. The conflict has hindered social cohesion and chronic poverty has additionally weakened humanitarian and development efforts.
The Resilience Programme is a value chain support programme that is implemented for the benefit of local smallholder farming. It is jointly implemented by the World Food Programme (WFP) and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO),in collaboration with the DRC Government (at national and local level) and cooperatingpartners, including national and international humanitarian organizations.
The programme has achieved results in the following areas:
(a) Capacity building of community organizations;
(b) Conflict resolution and promotion of social cohesion;
(c) Gender equality and women's empowerment;
(d) Improving financial capacity and promoting inclusive financing;
(e) Strengthening the quantity and quality of agricultural production and processing capacities; and
(f) Post-harvest management and inclusive market access.
 
Specifically the following results have been achieved:
(a) Project beneficiaries are grouped in farmers organizations that are legally established and able to provide services to their members;
(b) Beneficiary communities are prepared to take measures to mitigate conflict and promote social cohesion, gender equality, peace and reconciliation;
(c) The conditions of women in their communities have improved as a result of the project's activities;
(d) Rural households have the financial capacity and strategic means to accumulate assets and capital and to seize diversified economic opportunities;
(e) Smallholder farmers have strengthened capacity for sustainable agricultural production (in quantity and quality) and food processing;
(f) Smallholder farmers have adopted techniques to improve post-harvest management and their access to markets is improved and inclusive.
